<h3>‚≠ï Script 4:10 The Forecaster (‚Ññ 163)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Blurb: </b>Someone is baiting Liz by sending her dioramas of crimes that are about to be committed. Worse, these &#8220;forecasts&#8221; are being brought to her new home address.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Static, distorted voice ]<br />
[ A hazel-colored eye flashes in extreme closeup ] [ Someone working with cardboard, colored paper, glue, dollhouse furniture and clay is constructing a diorama. The style is childlike, but the scene is not. It depicts a woman lying face down in a pool of water ]<br />
[ Static crackling ] [ Distorted voice ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Liz pours coffee ]<br />
Liz: I hate to leave you here with all this.<br />
Tom: No. I&#8217;m kind of looking forward to it. Me and Agnes hanging out in our new place, listen to some tunes, unpack a few boxes. Maybe even eat some strained pears.<br />
Liz: [ Laughs ] Everything&#8217;s coming together for us.<br />
Tom: Yeah.<br />
Liz: We&#8217;ve got Agnes back. We&#8217;ve got each other. I&#8217;m an agent again.<br />
Tom: Yeah, we got out of Reddington&#8217;s safe house. No more bodyguards. We have windows that we can look out of and actually see the sky. Not bad. It&#8217;s a new beginning. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Tom opens a package with his dozen or so fake passports ]<br />
Liz: It&#8217;s a lot to give up.<br />
Tom: No. [ Tom tosses the passports in the trash ] Believe me, it&#8217;s not.<br />
[ Agnes giggling ]<br />
Tom: Oh, sounds like someone&#8217;s ready to get her groove on. You know, I think we&#8217;re gonna go old school. I&#8217;m thinkin&#8217;&#8230; The Romantics.<br />
Liz: Oh! [ Chuckles ] Okay, now I&#8217;m jealous. [ Chuckles ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Liz grabs her coat and opens the front door then halts. On the floor is a diorama of a woman face down in a pool of water. A sign on a small piece of white paper on the diorama reads &#8220;PLEASE SAVE HER&#8221; ]<br />
Liz: Tom. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ A middle-aged woman drinking a green health concoction walks to the side of a swimming pool. She is alone. She puts down her drink, takes off her robe, and dives into the pool. She swims about half way across the pool, then she seizes up. Gasping, she struggles for air, clenching her chest. She is unable to gain control and drowns, face down in the pool ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Door thuds ] [ Liz arrives at work with the diorama ]<br />
Aram: Oh, oh. Agent Keen, that is so cool. I had no idea you were so artsy-craftsy.<br />
Liz: I just found this outside my front door.<br />
Aram: What? Like a gift?<br />
Liz: No, like a warning‚Äì or a cry for help.<br />
Aram: This is ghoulish. A drowning superwoman?<br />
Liz: That&#8217;s not a cape. That&#8217;s a judge&#8217;s robe. Federal Judge Trisha Culpepper drowned in her country club pool this morning. The guard at the club saw her enter around 8 AM and then, 30 minutes later, 9-1-1 received a call from an employee saying she drowned.<br />
Cooper: Someone made this diorama after learning about what happened and put it on your doorstep?<br />
Liz: No, the guard saw her at 8 AM. I found this around 7 AM‚Äì an hour before she drowned.<br />
Samar: Or was murdered by a killer who left this at your doorstep.<br />
Ressler: Well, do you think it might be somebody from your days at the Mobile Psych Unit?<br />
Liz: I already contacted the New York field office. They&#8217;re sending me my files now.<br />
Cooper: Get this to the lab for processing. Maybe we&#8217;ll get trace evidence or a print. Ressler, Navabi, get to the crime scene. Agent Keen, talk to Reddington. See if he can shed some light on this. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Pamela, a real estate agent is showing Red around an apartment. The apartment is decorated in white ‚Äì rugs, furniture, walls. A bowl of cream-colored roses is on the white marble-topped table and the pieces of a white ‚Äì all white ‚Äì zigsaw puzzle are spread out ]<br />
Pamela: Everything&#8217;s included. The last tenant left the furnishings behind. Just disappeared.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;d have to stick to champagnes and white Burgundies. One spill of a red varietal and this heavenly sanctuary would look like a crime scene.<br />
Pamela: White wines are good. I drink white.<br />
<b>Red:</b> But would I be capable? Let&#8217;s say somebody stops by with a Domaine de la Roman√©e-Conti, and it&#8217;s a &#8217;78! [ Laughs ]<br />
Pamela: [ Lowered voice, to Dembe ] Couldn&#8217;t he just drink it in the kitchen?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I just had a revelation. I could drink it in the kitchen! [ Laughs ]<br />
Pamela: So I&#8217;ll draw up the paperwork. Month to month, right, Mr. Homan?<br />
[ Knock on door. Liz enters ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Thank you, Pamela.<br />
[ Door closes ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Liz: I don&#8217;t want to know how you did it or what it says about the fate of our country that you were able to, but I wanna thank you for getting the President of the United States to pardon me.<br />
<b>Red:</b> As my grandmother used to say, it&#8217;s good to have friends in low places. When Dembe said you had a case, I thought, how quaint. It&#8217;s not.<br />
Liz: You looked at the photos I sent.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes. Judge Culpepper was above reproach, which means many people would like her dead, but none I could connect to you in any way.<br />
Liz: I&#8217;ve looked at every case file from my time at the Mobile Psych Unit, and no suspect&#8217;s an obvious match.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Any leads off the diorama?<br />
Liz: A partial print, but inconclusive.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;ll have a team outside your apartment within the hour.<br />
Liz: No, that&#8217;s not necessary. Whoever&#8217;s doing this does not want to hurt me. They wanna match wits with me, see if I can catch them.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Do not take this lightly. This is your next Blacklister.<br />
Liz: But you don&#8217;t even know who this is.<br />
<b>Red:</b> He&#8217;s killed a federal judge, which means he goes after high profile targets. He left clues at your doorstep, which means it&#8217;s a game to him, one he&#8217;ll keep playing until you stop him. You&#8217;re being baited, Elizabeth, taunted by a killer who knows where you live.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Tom is unpacking, while Agnes giggles and wiggles in her bouncer swing ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
[ The Romantics&#8217; ‚ô™ &#8220;What I Like About You&#8221; playing ]<br />
‚ô™ hey! ‚ô™
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Tom sings along, pretending a broom is a standing mic ] </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ what I like about you ‚ô™<br />
‚ô™ you hold me tight ‚ô™
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Agnes wiggles and giggles ] </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ keep on whisperin&#8217; in my ear ‚ô™<br />
‚ô™ tell me all the things that I wanna hear ‚ô™<br />
‚ô™ &#8217;cause it&#8217;s true ‚ô™<br />
‚ô™ what I like ‚ô™<br />
‚ô™ that&#8217;s what I like about you ‚ô™
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Giggles ] </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ what I like about you ‚ô™
</p></blockquote>
<p>Tom: Oh, come on. You don&#8217;t think I can sing? I see you laughing at me.<br />
[ Footsteps approach ] </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ that&#8217;s what I like about you ‚ô™<br />
‚ô™ that&#8217;s what I like about you ‚ô™<br />
‚ô™ hey! ‚ô™<br />
‚ô™ uh, huh, huh, hey, hey, hey, hey ‚ô™
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Tom sees shadows and hears a rustling outside the door. He grabs a box cutter and opens the door. There is another diorama on the floor with a sign &#8220;PLEASE STOP THIS.&#8221; This diorama shows a man in a park slain by someone on a cycle. Tom hears a door close and runs down the stairs of the building and out onto the street ]<br />
[ Horn honks ] [ Tom glimpses a figure in a hoodie hurrying away. He runs after the figure ]<br />
Tom: Hey! Stop! Stop!<br />
[ Horn honks ] [ Rather than pursue the person further, Tom turns around and rushes back inside the apartment building ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Agnes: [ Whining ]<br />
Tom: Hey. Hi. [ Giggles ] Hi! What you doin&#8217;? Hi! Come here, come here, come here.<br />
[ Agnes fussing ] [ Tom picks her up ]<br />
Tom: I know. I got you. I got you. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Samar: We&#8217;ve been going through the judge&#8217;s docket. Six months back, six months ahead. There&#8217;s a total of 53 cases.<br />
Ressler: Seems like revenge killing, retaliation for a ruling. The next one could be a witness, a lawyer.<br />
Samar: First a drowning, then a shooting. What&#8217;s the pattern? The victims can&#8217;t be random.<br />
Aram: The clock tower. I&#8217;ve been thinking about it. It&#8217;s, uh, it&#8217;s familiar. And then I realized I remembered it from Mr. Mathiesen&#8217;s seventh grade civics class. We studied all the great DC buildings in that class‚Äì<br />
Cooper: Aram, the building.<br />
Aram: I think it&#8217;s the old Post Office tower.<br />
Ressler: Well, this clock [ in the diorama ] says 12:30. If that&#8217;s PM, we&#8217;re in trouble.<br />
Cooper: Alert the MPD. Tell them we have actionable intel that a homicide is about to be attempted.<br />
Ressler: Right, I&#8217;ll mobilize surveillance. We&#8217;re gonna take this guy down. [ To Liz: ] He&#8217;s not getting anywhere near your place this time. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ In the white apartment, Red receives a visitor ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Geoffroy! Thank you for coming.<br />
Geoffroy Keino: I was surprised you called me, Mr. Reddington. What can I do for you?<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Chuckles ] Tell me about cobalt.<br />
Geoffroy: Every cellphone battery requires at least 3 grams of it. Laptops, even more.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m told Iniko&#8217;s investing in cobalt mines. I want in.<br />
Geoffroy: You&#8217;re gonna have to talk to Iniko about that. Shall I set a meeting?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Do you recognize this apartment?<br />
Geoffroy: No. Should I?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Belonged to a dear friend of mine, a former acquaintance of Iniko&#8217;s. I say &#8220;former&#8221; because Iniko had him killed right where you&#8217;re standing. Imagine all that blood on this very carpet. Amazing. It&#8217;s like it never happened, as if he never existed.<br />
Geoffroy: Why are you telling me this?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m interested in the mines, but not in doing business with Iniko.<br />
Geoffroy: [ Chuckles ] You&#8217;re asking me to betray my boss.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes, I&#8217;m prepared to make a substantial contribution to the venture.<br />
Geoffroy: He would kill me if he found out.<br />
<b>Red:</b> If he were still alive.<br />
Geoffroy: Look, Mr. Reddington, I don&#8217;t know what you&#8217;re suggesting‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m suggesting that this is your moment if you&#8217;re smart enough to seize it. Iniko&#8217;s loyal only to himself. He suffers you because your uncle has the ear of the President. You&#8217;re a patronage hire who buys Iniko good will with the powers that be. But when they go, and they will, you&#8217;ll go. Like my dear friend who bled all over this white carpet. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ In the park by the old Post Office tower, Aram is seated on a park bench with his laptop. Ressler, Samar and Liz scan the crowd and traffic. A grey-haired square-jawed businessman walks hurriedly through the park ]<br />
Aram: All right, I&#8217;m tapped into every camera in the area, and I am not seeing anything.<br />
Ressler: I hate bikes.<br />
Samar: They&#8217;re good for the environment.<br />
Ressler: Well, there&#8217;s no way to tell which one&#8217;s our perp.<br />
Liz: I just got word from the lab. They were able to pull a print from a handrail outside my apartment. It matches a partial we pulled from the first model. Suspect&#8217;s name is Fiona Driscoll. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Clock tower chimes 12:30 ] [ Horn honks in distance ]<br />
Aram: Uh, guys? We&#8217;re looking for a guy on a bike, right?<br />
[ Motorcycle engine revs ]<br />
Aram: I think that bike might be a motorcycle.<br />
[ The motorcycle hones in on the businessman ] [ Liz tackles the businessman to the ground and covers him ]<br />
Liz: Down! Get down!<br />
[ üí• The motorcyclist fires off several shots üí•üí• but misses ] [ The motorcycle&#8217;s engine revs and it speeds away ]<br />
Liz: You okay?<br />
Businessman: Yeah. Who the hell are you?<br />
Liz: FBI. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Iniko is enjoying lunch in a restaurant. Red sits down ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Iniko. I understand you&#8217;re in town to bribe a congressman. Tell me, what&#8217;s the going rate to get someone to ignore rape, slave labor, child soldiers, child brides?<br />
Iniko: I was told you had a business proposition, not a lecture.<br />
<b>Red:</b> The cobalt mines. I want in.<br />
Iniko: Not interested.<br />
<b>Red:</b> So lecture then. You&#8217;ve been betrayed by a trusted employee. I recently experienced a similar betrayal. So I know that it&#8217;s a bitter pill, especially since in our line of work, betrayal requires swift and decisive retribution.<br />
Iniko: And you will give me the name in exchange for a cut of the mines.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Twenty-five percent. Assuming you can verify what I tell you is true.<br />
Iniko: Twenty.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Geoffroy Keino. He approached me about investing in the mines if I agreed to kill you. His terms were very generous, so you can imagine how tempted I was. But as I mentioned, I have recently felt the sting of duplicity. And I simply couldn&#8217;t bring myself to facilitate such a betrayal of someone else, even someone so loathsome.<br />
Iniko: [ Chuckles ] And people say there is no honor among thieves. Stay. Have some foie gras.<br />
<b>Red:</b> No, thank you. I find it difficult to enjoy foie gras. All those poor geese, all those painfully engorged livers.<br />
Iniko: [ Chuckles ] In my opinion, some lives are inconsequential, and delicious.<br />
<b>Red:</b> We&#8217;ll be in touch with any further developments.<br />
[ Red and Dembe leave ]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Dembe: You shouldn&#8217;t use her like that.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Not here.<br />
As a story to get what you want. It&#8217;s disrespectful. Kate doesn&#8217;t deserve that. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Engine revs ] [ Tires screech ] [ Panting ] [ Cellphone beeps, speed dials ]<br />
Motorcyclist: Hey, it&#8217;s me. We have a problem. It&#8217;s about Milch. The feds were waiting when I got there. I don&#8217;t know how, but they knew it was gonna happen.<br />
Older Man: All right, calm down. Don&#8217;t talk to anybody. I&#8217;ll call my source downtown, see what he knows. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Cellphone beeps ] [ Door opens ]<br />
Liz: Hello, Ms. Driscoll.<br />
Fiona Driscoll: Agent Keen, I think there&#8217;s been a terrible mistake.<br />
[ Door closes ]<br />
Liz: We have your fingerprints on the renderings of crime scenes you left outside my home.<br />
Fiona: I know what you must be thinking. I know how this looks.<br />
Ressler: Well, it looks like you were taunting Agent Keen, giving her details of the murders you were about to commit, seeing if she could stop you.<br />
Liz: We found traces of aconitine in the judge&#8217;s system. You poisoned her and then tried to murder Marlon Milch.<br />
Fiona: Marlon Milch? Is that his name?<br />
Ressler: Come on. You&#8217;re trying to say that you don&#8217;t know the name of the man that you tried to kill?<br />
Fiona: You&#8217;ve got it all wrong. I wasn&#8217;t trying to kill these people. I was trying to save them. I left the models for you because I wasn&#8217;t sure what else to do.<br />
Liz: Models of crime scenes made before the crimes were committed.<br />
Ressler: So how do you explain that? Unless you&#8217;re the killer.<br />
Fiona: They&#8217;re premonitions.<br />
Ressler: All right, tell us about the victims. A respected judge, a controversial businessman. Why target them? Why are they connected?<br />
Fiona: I only know what I see in the dioramas.<br />
Liz: Why haven&#8217;t you taken these premonitions to the police?<br />
Fiona: I have. They looked at me like I&#8217;m crazy. That&#8217;s why I came to you, Agent Keen. I saw you at the grocery store, recognized you from the news. I followed you home because I thought you&#8217;d understand. The pardon. You know what it&#8217;s like to be judged harshly, how it feels not to be believed.<br />
Liz: When did these premonitions start?<br />
Fiona: Just over two years ago.<br />
Liz: So there are more dioramas. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ A key unlocks a padlock on a door ]<br />
Fiona: At first, it was butterflies with glitter, and things like that. Then they turned into&#8230; these.<br />
[ In the room there are shelves and shelves of dioramas ]<br />
Fiona: There are 42 in all, each forecasting some horrible tragedy‚Äì murders, accidents, catastrophes. This is Flight 361. It crashed in the Andes last year. Sometimes they come with vivid detail. Others are more&#8230; impressionistic.<br />
Liz: How do you get these visions?<br />
Fiona: Oh, no. They&#8217;re not mine. I don&#8217;t see them.<br />
[ Door creaking ]<br />
Fiona: Her name&#8217;s Maggie. She&#8217;s 9.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Fiona: Maggie&#8217;s mind is&#8230; different. She suffers from what doctors call a constellation of birth defects, the result of fetal rubella. Heart problems, hearing impairment, any number of developmental issues. But I feel like she understands more than they think. Just because she can&#8217;t talk doesn&#8217;t mean she has nothing to say.<br />
Liz: Maggie&#8217;s visions, when did they start?<br />
Fiona: February, two years ago. She drew me a picture, this terrible image. A train and a bus crashing. Bodies everywhere. The next day, a bus was struck by a train in the Ukraine. 13 people were killed, another 6 injured, and she knew. Somehow, Maggie knew.<br />
Liz: Were they any changes in your life at the time? Had you moved? Did she change schools?<br />
Fiona: No. Nothing. We&#8217;ve always been around the same close circle of friends. Our world is very small.<br />
Liz: What is she working on now?<br />
Fiona: The next one. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Aram: I cross-checked the dioramas against verifiable incidents, and in each case, the incident and the diorama were a match. This July, a sailboat washes ashore south of Naples. Both the owner and his wife are lost a sea. [ Beep ] Two months earlier, a Jaipur factory fire kills 18. [ Beeping ] A bus accident in Miami. A mass shooting in Madrid.<br />
Liz: These aren&#8217;t just crimes, these are catastrophic events happening all around the world.<br />
Cooper: You say the mother claims the child predicted all this?<br />
Ressler: That&#8217;s what she says.<br />
Cooper: I don&#8217;t believe in premonitions. So prior knowledge of these events has to have come from somewhere.<br />
Samar: We&#8217;re running down a list of everyone who interacts with the child, but the list is not promising.<br />
Cooper: You said she can&#8217;t speak.<br />
Liz: Her mother says she has an undiagnosed cognitive disorder.<br />
Cooper: Pull her medical file. I want to know exactly what we can and cannot expect her to be able to tell us about these premonitions. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Cellphone vibrates ]<br />
Liz: Tom.<br />
Tom: Hey. Is everything okay? Three agents from the Bureau are camped outside.<br />
Liz: Cooper insisted, but the person who delivered the dioramas wasn&#8217;t the killer. It was a mom whose daughter somehow knows about crimes that haven&#8217;t been committed yet.<br />
Tom: Okay, well, that&#8217;s a little weird. [ Agnes fussing ] And creepy. And if the mom knows where we live, maybe the killer does, too.<br />
Liz: Tell me about Agnes.<br />
Tom: She is blissfully unaware that her parents are talking about a serial killer. Liz, what can I do? How can I help?<br />
Liz: You are helping.<br />
Tom: You know what I mean.<br />
Liz: I do. And I appreciate that. But for now, we&#8217;re good. I&#8217;ll call you if anything changes.<br />
Tom: Sure. Okay. Go‚Äì go do your thing.<br />
[ Phone beep, thuds ] [ Fussing ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />

Liz: All right, bon app√©tit.<br />
[ Tim hands Liz a small bundle ]<br />
Liz: What is this?<br />
[ Liz opens the bundle. It&#8217;s Tim&#8217;s fake passports ]<br />
Tom: It&#8217;s a promise. I lied when I said it wasn&#8217;t a lot to give up.<br />
Liz: Yeah. It wasn&#8217;t a lie, it was a hope.<br />
Tom: Yeah, I&#8230; I want this to work.<br />
Liz: And wondering whether or not that&#8217;s possible is totally natural.<br />
Tom: Right. But what isn&#8217;t natural for me, anyway, is talking about that, so&#8230; [ Inhales deeply ] it&#8217;s my promise, to share this doubt with you.<br />
Liz: Thank you.<br />
Tom: I threw those out this morning, yet here they are.<br />
Liz: Good. This is exactly where they belong. David&#8230; Lucas, and&#8230; Kaya. I used to be scared of those guys. Not anymore.<br />
Tom: [ Chuckles ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Knock on door ]<br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 4:10 The Forecaster (‚Ññ 163)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Blurb: </b>The US witness protection list has been stolen by a group of female thieves called The Harem. Dembe has confided in Liz that Red murdered Kate (&#8220;Mr Kaplan&#8221;).
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
[ <b>Note</b>: There are four members of <b>The Harem</b>:<br />
‚óè <b>Margot</b> is <b>The Leader</b>. Light brown hair, attractive, the oldest of the group (mid-thirties).<br />
‚óè <b>Sasha</b> is <b>Oriental</b> in appearance. She is the tech genius. She plans the heists.<br />
‚óè <b>Jessica</b> is <b>African American</b>, stunningly beautiful, colorfully dressed, gung ho, hyperactive and cheerful.<br />
‚óè <b>Emma</b> speaks with a <b>British</b> accent. She is blonde, plain and subdued compared to the others ]
</p></blockquote>

[ Two black SUVs pull up to large white marble mansion. Four guards get out ]<br />

[ Car alarm chirps ]<br />
[ One guard remains outside (dubbed &#8220;Lurch&#8221; by Margot); the others enter the mansion ] [ A black woman (Jessica) is talking on her cell phone outside the door of the mansion. Sasha removes a rifle from a bass violin case and mounts it from a perch looking down on the driveway ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ A blonde woman, very pregnant (Emma), walks inside the mansion ]<br />

[ Diamonds clatter ] </p>

<h2>üî¥ Script: 4:12 Natalie Luca (‚Ññ 184)</h2>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Program air date: 2/2/2017 in the US<br />
Permalink: <a href="http://wp.me/pDKwi-4b4" rel="nofollow">http://wp.me/pDKwi-4b4</a><br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 4:12 Natalie Luca (‚Ññ 184)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Blurb: </b>One of Red&#8217;s accountants is disappeared or dead ‚Äì along with a huge cache of cash (Red&#8217;s cash). The Task Force confronts an assassin who uses disease to kill.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Moldova, 14 years ago ]<br />
[ A little girl, five or so years old with long blonde hair, wakes up in a hospital room. She gets out of bed and leaves her room and calls for her Mama. Outside her door, a man is slouched against the wall, dead. She runs down the hall. Other people are dead, some covered with blood and vomit, lying here and there. She climbs halfway up a staircase and stops, peering down through the railings. Men enter in HAZMAT suits, looking like aliens. One sees the little girl and walks up to the staircase. They stare at one another ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Eight days ago ]<br />
[ A woman in her early 20s with long blonde hair pushes aside a bead curtain and enters a massage room. Red&#8217;s accountant Zach Smoll, who is the client, looks up from his prone position  on the table ]<br />
Zach: You&#8217;re new.<br />
[ The woman coats her hands with massage gel. She pulls back his towel, then gets up on the table and sits astride him ]<br />
Zach: Oh!<br />
Woman: [ Whispers ] Roll over.<br />
Zach: Okay. [ Giggles ]<br />
Woman: What&#8217;s your name?<br />
Zach: Zach.<br />
Woman: [ Repeats, softly ] Zach.<br />
[ She kisses him then leaves ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ A second female masseuse enters and begins to coat her hands with gel ]<br />
Masseuse: I see you&#8217;re ready.<br />
Zach: What happened to the new girl?<br />
Masseuse: What new girl?<br />
[ Suddenly Zach&#8217;s back and hands break out in an angry, rapidly blistering purple red rash ]<br />
[ The Masseuse gasps ] [ Zach vomits ] [ In less than a minute Zach is dead ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ At Red&#8217;s accountants&#8217; basement operations site ]<br />
 <b>Red:</b> How much? Smoll was cleaning over two hundred million. How much was lost?<br />
Abe: All of it.<br />
 <b>Red:</b> Thank you, Abe.<br />
[ Liz enters ]<br />
Liz: Problems?<br />
 <b>Red:</b> Yes. [ Clears throat ] Transactions vital to my interests failed to be tendered.<br />
Liz: What kinds of transactions?<br />
 <b>Red:</b> It seems that a bid I made on the Whistler Cruise Line wasn&#8217;t tendered because my accountant dropped dead before he could transfer the funds. In addition, millions are missing that the same accountant was in the process of laundering.<br />
Liz: I think I&#8217;ve heard enough.<br />
 <b>Red:</b> It appears my operation is under seige.<br />
Liz: And this affects the fate of the free world how?<br />
 <b>Red:</b> Not at all. However, in order for me to be useful to your task force, I have to maintain a certain stature in the criminal underworld. From time to time, I am compelled to rely on your Bureau&#8217;s support in that endeavor. This is one of those times. The interest I hoped to acquire from Whistler Cruise Lines was sold to a long-standing rival, Baldur Magnusson. Rumors have circulated that he assassinated my accountant to secure the deal.<br />
Liz: What do you need from us?<br />
 <b>Red:</b> Some help to determine who murdered my man Jack Smoll. If I can&#8217;t staunch the bleeding Smoll&#8217;s death has precipitated, all of our work could come to a grinding and permanent halt. I&#8217;m under attack, Elizabeth, and I need to find out by whom.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Liz: Roughly 14 hours ago, Zack Smoll was found dead in the Gentle Bliss Massage Parlor. ME&#8217;s initial report describes symptoms consistent with acute meningitis.<br />
Cooper: How does Reddington know Smoll didn&#8217;t contract meningitis naturally?<br />
Liz: He didn&#8217;t say. But if he&#8217;s coming to us with this, it means he&#8217;s desperate.<br />
Samar: You may think you&#8217;re paid enough to serve the public&#8217;s interest and Reddington&#8217;s. Personally, I don&#8217;t.<br />
Ressler: If someone killed Reddington&#8217;s accountant, you think he&#8217;s gonna want us to just put him in jail? I mean, the second we find him, he&#8217;s gonna insist we turn him over so he can make an example by murdering him.<br />
Cooper: I agree. Agent Keen, tell Reddington he&#8217;s on his own.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Aram&#8217;s computer ü¶Ü*quacks* ü¶Ü ]<br />
Aram: Uh, guys, Smoll&#8217;s body has just been flagged by the CDC. They&#8217;ve rerouted it to a level four biocontainment lab.<br />
Ressler: What does that mean?<br />
Liz: It means whatever killed Smoll is a lot more dangerous than meningitis.<br />
Cooper: Get to the CDC. See what you can find out.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Liz: Any idea what we&#8217;re dealing with?<br />
Doctor Nina: Luschen&#8217;s disease. It&#8217;s a form of viral meningitis. Symptoms include sudden high fever, stiffened neck, reddish purple rash, seizure, respiratory failure and death.<br />
Ressler: How contagious is it?<br />
Doctor Nina: This strain&#8217;s mutated such that it&#8217;s transmitted via physical contact. Sweat, saliva, even the lightest touch can be lethal. Good news is it doesn&#8217;t survive outside a host. Symptoms present almost immediately after exposure, followed by death in only minutes, which is, ironically, the one saving grace of the disease.<br />
Ressler: How so?<br />
Dr Nina: It can&#8217;t travel. The victim&#8217;s incapacitated before he can transmit it.<br />
Liz: So how did Smoll get infected?<br />
Dr Nina: Lipstick. We found traces of it around the victim&#8217;s mouth. Based on the sample, whoever left it behind should have been dead long before she had the chance to even kiss our victim.<br />
Ressler: So, who is she? Why isn&#8217;t she dead?<br />
Dr Nina: Well, for the moment, Agent Ressler, that remains a mystery.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Aram laughs in excitement ]<br />
Aram: Oh ho ho! I found our suspect.<br />
Samar: Good for you.<br />
Aram: Okay, uh, what&#8217;s going on?<br />
Samar: Nothing. I&#8217;m fine.<br />
Aram: Really? Because you seems upset. And before, uh, with Mr Cooper, about not getting paid enough ‚Ä¶<br />
Samar: I just lost it with the ladies in payroll. They gave me your check instead of mine, because, you know, we both have brown faces.<br />
Aram: I&#8217;m sure that was a mistake.<br />
Samar: You make 32% more than I do.<br />
Aram: Oh, you opened my check.<br />
Samar: I have a PhD from the London School of Economics‚Äì<br />
Aram: Maybe it&#8217;s because you&#8217;re on loan from Mossad‚Äì<br />
Samar: I have the same clearances and responsibilities‚Äì<br />
Aram: Actually, technically‚Äì<br />
Samar: And people actually shoot at me.<br />
Aram: That is true. Okay. you should probably say something to Mr Cooper.<br />
[ Cooper appears ]<br />
Cooper: Say what?<br />
Samar: Aram has a suspect.<br />
Aram: Yes. Uh, the suspect. Uh, the suspect. Yes. So I found a partial angle from the security camera behind the massage parlor. Check it out. Okay, the CDC has only one other recorded outbreak of Luschen&#8217;s in the U.S. A pawn broker in Maryland. The local coroner wrote it off as natural causes. But the weird thing is his pawn shop was robbed the day he died. And so, I dug up some security feeds and look who was there.<br />
Cooper: The same woman at both outbreaks. One a robbery, the other an assassination.<br />
Aram: And in a bad disguise at both.<br />
Samar: What if it&#8217;s not a disguise. Look at the time code. It&#8217;s July. In Maryland it must have been 90 degrees. So either she&#8217;s sick, she has fevers, chills, or she doesn&#8217;t want anyone else to get sick, so she&#8217;s using a protective covering to mitigate contagion.<br />
Aram: So she&#8217;s not trying to start a pandemic.<br />
Cooper: Well, whatever she&#8217;s doing, if we don&#8217;t find her soon, someone else is going to die in the process. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Natalie Luca is lying on her side, in preparation for a spinal tap which will be administered by her boyfriend, Malik Roumain ]<br />
Malik: I wish there was another way.<br />
Natalie: It&#8217;s okay.<br />
Malik: But we need it for the next stage.<br />
Natalie: You don&#8217;t have to explain. This is what we both want. Just do it.<br />
[ Malik injects her with a long needle. Natalie&#8217;s face contorts in pain ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Boston, MA ]<br />
[ Baldur Magnusson&#8217;s phone rings ]<br />
Baldur: What do you want?<br />
 <b>Red:</b> Are the rumors true that you&#8217;re responsible for the death of my accountant, Zack Smoll?<br />
Baldur: The truth doesn&#8217;t matter. It&#8217;s about appearances. And at the moment it appears to virtually anyone who gives a damn that I killed Smoll, and your failure to retaliate is proof of your weakness. Whether I killed him or not is immaterial. You have no choice but to come for me.<br />
 <b>Red:</b> And you for me.<br />
Baldur: Which begs the question, why bother with a phone call?<br />
 <b>Red:</b> Because we&#8217;ve known each other for a long time. We understand each other&#8217;s organizations, if Cristobal acted without your authority or someone forced your hand, tell me. We can try and sort it out. After all, you&#8217;re a bit long in the tooth for a street brawl.<br />
Baldur: You think so?<br />
[ Beeps ] [ Hangs up ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red&#8217;s cell phone beeps ]<br />
 <b>Red:</b> I&#8217;ve reviewed the case file you sent.<br />
Liz: And you&#8217;ve got something?<br />
 <b>Red:</b> You know, many ancient cultures shares a common figure, a god or demon who brought disease to humanity. The Finns called her Loviatar, the Yoruba people knew her as Shapona. The Greeks of course immortalized Pandora. Odd that they&#8217;re always women. Have you ever heard of Mary Mallon?<br />
Liz: Should I have?<br />
 <b>Red:</b> She was a cook for the New York elite in the late 19th Century. When an alarming number of high society swells came down with typhoid fever, a research scientist traced the outbreak to a woman with the rare ability to carry the disease without suffering its effects or exhibiting any outward symptoms. Earning her the name‚Äì<br />
Liz: Typhoid Mary.<br />
 <b>Red:</b> Correct. You&#8217;re looking for an asymptomatic carrier of Luschen&#8217;s Disease. To find your suspect, you need to know when and where was the outbreak that she survived. And, hurry. There&#8217;s a reason the plague-bringers were the most feared among the ancient deities.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Natalie and Malik are eating a meal. They are seated alongside each other but separated by the vinyl panel of a bio-containment unit ]<br />
Natalie: You&#8217;ve got that little crease between your brow. Right here. [ She points to her own brow ] It always happens when you&#8217;re upset.<br />
Malik: The spinal tap didn&#8217;t yield the results that I was expecting. And we still need specialized equipment, which means that‚Ä¶<br />
Natalie: More money. More people.<br />
Malik: I found another opportunity, that we- we can handle, that you can handle, I&#8217;m sure of it. Please look at me. I&#8217;m gonna figure this out. I swear it. I just need a little more time. [ He puts his hand against the vinyl ] We&#8217;re so close.<br />
[ Natalie places her hand against his, separated by the impermeable barrier. She smiles ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Tom is arriving home with Agnes in a stroller ]<br />
Tom: All right, home sweet home, baby. All right, c&#8217;mon you.<br />
[ Tom succeeds in unlocking the door, but quickly he senses something is off. He leaves Agnes at the door&#8217;s threshhold and, gun drawn, surveys the room. It is only Red ]<br />
 <b>Red:</b> Please excuse the intrusion.<br />
Tom: She&#8217;s not here.<br />
 <b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m not here to see Elizabeth.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
 <b>Red:</b> What do you know about Edgar Legate?<br />
Tom: When it comes to assassins, he&#8217;s the gold standard. Nobody&#8217;s ever seen the guy.<br />
 <b>Red:</b> Precisely. Because he doesn&#8217;t exist. Legate is an elaborate fiction, a bogeyman I created.<br />
[ Dembe entertains Agnes. Agnes giggles ]<br />
Tom: No. no, Legate is real, all right. I know at least six jobs the guy&#8217;s done.<br />
 <b>Red:</b> Or so you believe. Edgar Legate is nothing more than a name I employ to take credit for various killings for which I or my associates are responsible. One of my competitors, Baldur Magnusson, is actively seeking a reliable independent contractor to kill me, someone I won&#8217;t see coming. I think Legate would fit the bill nicely.<br />
Tom: And you want me to become Legate.<br />
 <b>Red:</b> I thought maybe.<br />
Tom: Forget it. I&#8217;m not gonna play dress-up assassin so you can kill someone I never met.<br />
 <b>Red:</b> I don&#8217;t need you to become Legate to kill Magnusson. I need you to become Legate so Magnusson will hire you to kill me.<br />
Tom: You want me to deliver him to me.<br />
 <b>Red:</b> Yes. If you can find a sitter. [ Red smiles merrily at Agnes ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ At the Post Office  ]<br />
[ Telephone rings in the distance ]<br />
Cooper: I wanna talk to you after this.<br />
Samar: Yeah, sure.<br />
Aram: So I looked into Reddington&#8217;s Typhoid Mary angle and I found something. The first recorded outbreak of Luschen&#8217;s in human beings occurred in rural Moldova in 2002. A family of nine wiped out except for one daughter Natalie Luca. She was taken to a local clinic, but the outbreak was deemed too much for them to handle.<br />
Cooper: How did she get out of Moldova?<br />
Aram: The World Health Organization called in Hawthorne Biologics, a company that specializes in infectious disease response. They brought the girl back to their research clinic outside Alexandria for further treatment.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Hawthorne Biologics MD: I had no idea Natalie was capable of anything like this. We care for dozens of patients who are too infectious to live outside of strict quarantine. Out of all of them, Natalie was the sweetest, the kindest.<br />
Ressler: If she was so infectious, how come she&#8217;s at large?<br />
MD: We did our best to give her a normal life. But she was young, determined to be independent. We did everything we could to dissuade her from leaving. But eventually, we had no choice but to comply with her wishes.<br />
Samar: How is that possible? She was infected with a deadly contagion.<br />
MD: We had no legal right to hold her. She was young. She was in love.<br />
Ressler: In love? With who?<br />
MD: Malik Roumain. He was a promising young bio research tech.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Malik&#8217;s reflection appears in a van&#8217;s rearview mirror ]<br />
Malik: They&#8217;re here.<br />
[ Natalie prepares to get out of the van ]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Samar: But they couldn&#8217;t touch each other?<br />
MD: No. It&#8217;s hard to imagine in the absence of physical contact, but certainly not impossible. He advocated for her, agreed to take responsibility for her quarantine, see to her needs. We agreed to a year-long break from testing in exchange for Malik submitting regular reports. Until you called, we had no idea they were gone. The reports kept coming in, so we assumed they were still at the house we&#8217;d provided. It turns out, they moved out months ago.<br />
Ressler: You didn&#8217;t check on them?<br />
MD: We wanted to respect their privacy. If you need anything further from me, please don&#8217;t hesitate to call. If anything were to happen to this child, I don&#8217;t know that I&#8217;ll be able to forgive myself.<br />
Ressler: If I were you, I&#8217;d be more worried about what might happen to everyone else.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Natalie emerges from the van and approaches a guard for an armored car ]<br />
Natalie: Hi. I&#8217;m so sorry, but we&#8217;re doing this scavenger hunt for my sorority, and I need to kiss two guys with a gun<br />
Guard: Seriously?<br />

Guard: Do your worst.<br />

‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Guard #2 emerges with two heavy leather bags to load into their vehicle. He opens the door to see the first guard dead inside. Immediately, Guard #2 is also overtaken. Vomiting he falls to the ground. ] [ Grunts softly ] [ Coughs ] [ Gurgling ]<br />
[ Malik walks over and retrieves the two leather bags ]<br />
[ Van door opens, closes ] [ Driver door opens, closes ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Volker Graves: If you had allowed me secure the facility as I requested, Malik never could&#8217;ve broken her out in the first place.<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ At the Post Office ]<br />
Liz: Malik Roumain born to immigrant parents. Full-boat to Berkeley at 17. The American dream. By 23, he had his PhD in biochemistry from Johns Hopkins and turned down a number of highly paid offers to accept a post-doc at Hawthorne.<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ In lobby of a hotel ] [ Indistinct conversations ] [ Cellphone chirps ]<br />
Tom: [ Quietly ] He&#8217;s here.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />

[ Red appears ]<br />

[ Dembe and Tom rough up the room, breaking a lamp, pouring blood on the couch and floor, dropping rifle shells on the floor ]<br />
 <b>Red:</b> [ Continues ] By the time our little charade is finished, Magnusson will be scouring the town desperate to hire your killer. Not to worry, Myron, we&#8217;ll have you out of there in a jiffy.<br />
[ Myron is shown being zipped into a body bag on a gurney, and wheeled out. He is unharmed ]<br />

[ As the gurney is rolled through the hotel lobby, Tom is reading a newspaper. He rises and leaves, making sure the attentive concierge notices him ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Ressler: The CDC confirmed the victims of the armored truck robbery died of Luschen&#8217;s.<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ In the hotel lobby ]<br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 4:13 Isabella Stone(‚Ññ 34)</h3>

<h2>üî¥ Script: 4:15 The Apothecary (‚Ññ 49)</h2>

<h3>‚≠ï Script 4:15 The Apothecary (‚Ññ 49)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Blurb: </b> Red needs to find out who in his organization has seized control of his accounts and threatens his life.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red&#8217;s secret flat ]<br />
[ Tropical music playing ] [ Dembe uncorks a bottle of Scotch ]<br />
Dembe: Raymond. Are you sure about this? Bringing them all together in one location. It&#8217;s dangerous. [ Scotch pours ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> One of our most trusted confidantes intends to do irrevocable damage to the organization. Needs to be confronted swiftly.<br />
Dembe: It&#8217;s dangerous.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Swallows, exhales ] There&#8217;s a traitor in the family. I intend to find them.<br />
Dembe: And if something goes wrong? </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red is in a hospital bed in a mobile surgical unit struggling for breath as a doctor holds a ventilator mask to his face ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Gasps, coughing loudly ]<br />
Dr Haverkamp: Hold on. Hold on. No, just‚Äì hold on.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Where am I?<br />
Haverkamp: Keep breathing. Keep‚Äì Slow. Good.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Groans ] What&#8217;s going on?<br />
Haverkamp: Mr. Reddington, my name is Dr. Haverkamp. I&#8217;m an on-call specialist on your code 77 team, and you had an emergency.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Gasping ] Why can&#8217;t‚Äì why can&#8217;t I breathe?<br />
Haverkamp: Give the medication a minute. Just give it a minute.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Gasping ]<br />
Haverkamp: I need you to listen. Do you know where you are? What do you remember?<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Gasps ] Dinner, restaurant. [ Gasping ] What&#8217;s wrong with me?<br />
Haverkamp: We&#8217;re not quite sure. We thought, at first, you may have had a series of mini strokes. But the MRIs, the EEGs, they ruled that out.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Where&#8217;s Dembe? Dembe will know.<br />
Haverkamp: I don&#8217;t know who that is, but the man who drove you here left as soon as you stabilized.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I don&#8217;t remember.<br />
Haverkamp: Mr. Reddington, I was told that you insist on a frank, unvarnished assessment of the situation. So here it is. You&#8217;re dying.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Exhales sharply ] How?<br />
Haverkamp: We believe you&#8217;ve been poisoned. We&#8217;re not sure how. But your symptoms are severe and they&#8217;re progressing at an alarming rate. The cocktail of steroids will stave off the symptoms for a short time, but unless we know how you were poisoned‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> How long can you keep me alive?<br />
Haverkamp: It&#8217;s hard to say. Uh, a day? Maybe two.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Exhales sharply ]<br />
[ Red begins ripping off the blood pressure cuff ]<br />
Haverkamp: What‚Äì what‚Äì No. No. What are you doing? You can&#8217;t‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> Your cellphone. Do you have a cellphone? </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red has his suit on, walking away from the medical setup ]<br />
Dr Haverkamp: Please, Mr. Reddington. You need medical attention. Your condition is critical. [ Pills rattle ] Where‚Äì are you going?<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ On phone ] Elizabeth. Gather the task force. I need your help ‚Äì to solve a murder. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Post Office ] [ Elevator door scrapes, slams ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Coughs ]<br />
Ressler: Uh, what&#8217;s going on?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Your prayers have been answered, Donald. [ Takes pills, swallows ] Ah. Apparently, I&#8217;m dying.<br />

<b>Red:</b> No, no, no. I&#8217;m fine. I&#8217;ve been poisoned.<br />
Cooper: Poisoned? By whom?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Someone within my organization. Someone with access to an offshore account that was used to fund recent attacks against me. 11 people had access to that account. Last evening, I called those 11 to a dinner to confront them. What happened next, I only remember pieces. The restaurant, what it looked like, not where it was. I remember holding a glass of wine, but not drinking it, although I&#8217;m sure I must have.<br />
Ressler: The poison‚Äì<br />
Samar: Where is Dembe?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Missing. I assume searching for or in the hands of the person who wants me dead.<br />
Cooper: You should be with your doctors.<br />
<b>Red:</b> They can&#8217;t identify the toxin.<br />
Cooper: A hospital, then.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;ve been told I have a day, two at most.<br />
Aram: No. That‚Äì that can&#8217;t be true.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I need you to find the pharmaco-toxicologist who, I believe, crafted the deadly cocktail and get the antidote from him.<br />
Ressler: What do you know about him?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Well‚Äì [ Coughs ]<br />
Liz: There&#8217;s a man. He told me he&#8217;s known as‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Grunts ] The Apothecary.<br />

Aram: He knew Helen Dahle. I&#8217;m sorry. Not know, know like he met her. He knew her medical history and he used it against her. Helen&#8217;s doctors think she went into a coma because of a reaction to a tree nut allergy, but the truth is, this Apothecary used some sort of complex, weaponized allergen to trigger the same reaction. Meaning her doctors‚Äì<br />
Liz: Were treating the symptoms, but not the cause.<br />
Cooper: How does this help us with Reddington?<br />
Ressler: We have to find out if Reddington has any pre-existing conditions, which one was targeted.<br />
Samar: And find an antidote to reverse the effects all in the next several hours.<br />
Aram: Right, that‚Äì that is the bad news.<br />
Samar: There&#8217;s good news?<br />
Aram: The lab did find one distinct element in the molecular structure of the drops taken from Robert Dahle&#8217;s apartment. A peptide unique to the venom of Bungarus flaviceps, also known as the red-headed krait [ a snake ] ‚Äì Incredibly rare.<br />
Liz: So it&#8217;s easy to trace.<br />
Aram: Only four suppliers in the world, and only one in America. A defunct reptile farm outside of Scranton, PA. Hightower Serpentarium. Owned by ‚Äì Asa Hightower, who, according to his license, still lives in an apartment on site.<br />

And then, on the 48th day, they swung the cell door wide and handed me a package. <h3>‚≠ï Script 4:16 Dembe Zuma (‚Ññ 10)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Blurb: </b>Red seeks out his bodyguard, Dembe Zuma, who is missing and may be responsible for poisoning him.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Washington DC ]<br />
[ Aram is showering. Janet (formerly &#8220;Elise&#8221;) startles him, then joins him in the shower ]<br />
Aram: Oh, my God. [ Laughs ] Don&#8217;t do that.<br />
Janet: What? This?<br />
Aram: Mmm No, that&#8217;s‚Äì that&#8217;s fine. Wait, how&#8217;d you get in?<br />

[ Bees buzzing ]<br />

<b>Red:</b> We just don&#8217;t know why.<br />
Vanessa: When I was a child, this place was a backbone of our honey business. My father knew a guy that needed a hideout. And he helped. And then another showed up. And another one. And soon, my parents were making more money from their Sanctum Corporation than they were from the bees. The fortune my parents made hiding criminals was in a Vulcan safe in our basement. The only people that knew that were the criminals that passed through. Someone came back and tried to steal the money. But while cutting through the lock with an acetylene torch, they set the house on fire. I was the only one that survived. Apitherapy is the only thing I&#8217;ve found effective in fighting the infection. Pheromones from the queen attract the swarm, and their stings and enzymes heal the scars.<br />
Liz: You have no idea which client did this, so you&#8217;re killing them all.<br />
Vanessa: If their file is in my parents&#8217; ledger, they deserve punishment for one thing or the other.<br />
<b>Red:</b> There&#8217;s an entry in that ledger I need to see. For your sake, I hope it&#8217;s not crossed off. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red searches through the ledger. He tears out a page ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Cooper: Kathryn Nemec is missing?<br />

<b>Red:</b> It&#8217;s time for us to meet and talk.<br />

You could breach the outer wall only to be faced with a heavily fortified gatehouse and barbican and a high inner wall lined with archers. Pity the poor foot soldier who made it that far. The architecture of my organization has risen stone by stone over decades. You can&#8217;t get inside to hurt me, Kate.<br />

<b>Red:</b> I never underestimated you, Werner. I just hoped things could work out.<br />
Von Hauser: [ Astonished ] Nikolaus?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Nikolaus has been on my payroll since I introduced him to you 25 years ago. I knew one day we would have to look each other in the eye and face the truth. And I knew it would be an event that one of us would not recover from. Your abiding love for your son was always evident to me, Werner. The loss of Hans‚Äì There are no words to duly express my remorse. I&#8217;m sorry for that. And I&#8217;m‚Äì I&#8217;m sorry for this.<br />
[ Red shoots Von Hauser üí•üí• ] [ Von Hauser grunts, falls back in a chair, dead ]<br />
Nikolaus: His men outside will be pulling in any minute. Some will stand with me, but it&#8217;s a house divided. Unless you want to join a civil war, you need to exit out back into the woods.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Thank you for your loyalty, Nikolaus. I&#8217;ll be in touch.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Liz: Where&#8217;s Agent Ressler?<br />
Samar: We know you were contracted to, what, erase some kind of memory, embed one?<br />
Dr Krilov: I want my lawyer.<br />
[ Liz grabs Krilov&#8217;s chin, turns his face toward her ]<br />
Liz: I&#8217;m not gonna ask again.<br />
Dr Krilov: I already told you, Princess, I&#8217;m not talking to you until my lawyer&#8217;s present.<br />
[ Liz takes a syringe and fills it with Propofol ]<br />
Samar: What are you doing?<br />
Liz: I told him I&#8217;m not gonna ask again.<br />
Samar: Liz, hang on.<br />
Dr Krilov: Are you serious? Come on. You are FBI. You think I actually believe you are going to inject that needle?<br />
Liz: You know, unfortunately, I don&#8217;t know much about Propofol. [ Bottle clatters ] I think it&#8217;s a general anesthetic? Can you even inject this directly into the arm?<br />
Dr Krilov: Stop it.<br />
Liz: I don&#8217;t know. You tell me. You&#8217;re the doctor, Princess.<br />
Samar: Agent Keen.<br />
[ Liz jabs the needle into Krilov&#8217;s arm ]<br />
Dr Krilov: Hey.<br />
Liz: Would mainlining this cause long-term damage to the heart?<br />
Samar: Liz.<br />
Liz: The lungs, the kidneys ‚Äì would it kill an old man?<br />
Dr Krilov: Okay, okay, stop it. I tell you.<br />
Liz: Keep talking.<br />
Dr Krilov: There is a house on the Potomac.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Liz: Aram, I have texted you an address. Laurel Hitchin&#8217;s house on the river. We&#8217;re on our way now.<br />
Cooper: Laurel Hitchin? What&#8217;s goin&#8217; on? What happened with Krilov?<br />
Liz: We have him in custody. His target? Kaplan&#8217;s target was Ressler.<br />
Cooper: My God.<br />
Aram: Wait, Agent Ressler? I thought he was in Philadelphia.<br />
Samar: He was, that&#8217;s why he was abducted and pumped full of drugs.<br />
Liz: We think Krilov somehow programmed Ressler to believe Hitchin abducted a witness that could connect her to Reven Wright&#8217;s murder.<br />
Cooper: Ressler wasn&#8217;t with Krilov when you found him?<br />
Samar: No. Krilov&#8217;s men had already moved him. They&#8217;re positioning him to go after Hitchin. We tried to call her to warn her, but we couldn&#8217;t reach her.<br />
Cooper: If Kaplan is behind this and her goal is to hurt Reddington, how does using Ressler to take out Hitchin help?<br />
Liz: Kaplan gave us the chance to abandon our relationship with Reddington, and we didn&#8217;t. Now she&#8217;ll take every step necessary to dismantle the task force, starting with Ressler.<br />
Samar: Without the task force, Reddington would be completely exposed.<br />
Aram: All right, I have the address. Routing backup to meet you there now.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Outside Laurel Hitchen&#8217;s house on the Potomac, Ressler is unconscious, propped up in the back seat of a car ]<br />
Nurse: Everything set?<br />
[ She injects Ressler ]<br />
Nurse: Let&#8217;s go. He&#8217;ll wake up soon.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Beeping ]<br />
[ Ressler wakens. Seeing the lake house and recognizing it, he runs in its direction, climbing over a fence. Confronted by a guard, he shoots üí• ]<br />
Guard: Aah! [ Grunts ]<br />
Ressler: Don&#8217;t.<br />
Guard: [ Groans ]<br />
Ressler: Come on.<br />
[ Grunts ] [ Handcuffs click ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Ressler enters Hitchin&#8217;s house. He finds Hitchin who is talking with an Asian Ambassador ]<br />
Ressler: Where is she? Where&#8217;s Linda?<br />
Hitchin: Ressler, that shot‚Äì<br />
Ressler: Where is she?!<br />
Ambassador: What is the meaning of this? Who is he?<br />
Ressler: Donald Ressler, FBI. Now Ms. Hitchin here is a prime suspect in Reven Wright&#8217;s murder.<br />
Hitchin: Agent Ressler isn&#8217;t well, Mr. Ambassador. He needs help.<br />
Ressler: Mr. Ambassador. Is he part of the Cabal as well?<br />
Hitchin: Yes, Donald. He is. We all are. It&#8217;s all one big, global conspiracy. And you weren&#8217;t invited to the party. Sorry.<br />
Ressler: [ To the Ambassador] Well, I think you should go.<br />
Ambassador: I will do no such thing.<br />
Ressler: Oh, I think you will. [ Points gun ] Now!<br />
Hitchin: It&#8217;s okay. I&#8217;m fine. He&#8217;s delusional, not dangerous.<br />
[ The Ambassador leaves ]<br />
Ressler: The witness, Linda McFaden. Where are you keeping her?<br />
Hitchin: Okay, first of all, I don&#8217;t know any Linda, but if you put the gun away, I&#8217;m sure we can work this out.<br />
Ressler: No, there&#8217;s no way you let her out of your sight, not when she&#8217;s the only person that can tie you to Reven Wright&#8217;s murder. See, I think you&#8217;re keeping her here. That&#8217;s what we&#8217;re gonna do. We&#8217;re gonna go through this place room by room. Now let&#8217;s go.<br />
Hitchin: Fine. Let&#8217;s go.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red and Dembe make their way through the woods behind the Von Hauser mansion ]<br />
Dembe: As soon as we hit the road, we&#8217;ll find a way to the jet.<br />
<b>Red:</b> The jet is sitting on one of Werner&#8217;s air strips. No doubt his men are on it right now drinking my Scotch and seeing who fits in my suits.<br />
Dembe: Then we&#8217;ll have to find another way out of here.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Without Werner or his contacts, shipping lanes, airfields, I can&#8217;t do anything from Gibraltar to the Urals. Every piece of his machinery is up in the air now, and where they land is anybody&#8217;s guess. For the time being, we&#8217;ll have to be comfortable with chaos.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Tires screeching. Gears shift, engine turns off. Samar and Liz get out of their SUV at Laurel Hitchin&#8217;s house. They see the wounded guard ]<br />
Liz: Stay with him.<br />
Samar: [ To the guard ] Help is on the way.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Inside ]<br />
Hitchin: Like I said, there&#8217;s nobody here.<br />
Ressler: Then you&#8217;re gonna tell me‚Äì you&#8217;re gonna tell me where you&#8217;re holding her‚Äì<br />
Liz: Ressler! Stand down.<br />
Ressler: Keen. I found a witness who saw Hitchin&#8217;s men dispose of Reven&#8217;s body.<br />
Liz: There is no witness.<br />
Hitchin: Thank you.<br />
Ressler: What are you talking about? I met her, okay? She told me everything.<br />
Hitchin: Listen to your partner, Agent Ressler. You&#8217;re ill. You need help.<br />
Liz: You&#8217;re not ill. Your memory was manipulated by Dr. Bogdan Krilov. We have him in custody.<br />
Ressler: No. I know what I saw. Trust me.<br />
Liz: No, you need to trust me. The Detective who reached out to you?<br />
Ressler: Elijah Bell.<br />
Liz: There is no Elijah Bell in the Philly PD. He works with Krilov. So does your witness.<br />
Ressler: No. No. I was at her house, okay? I was there when she was taken.<br />
Liz: By Krilov&#8217;s men. He staged the whole thing. Hitchin wasn&#8217;t involved. During the raid, you were knocked out, unconscious. That&#8217;s when Krilov started to work on you, implanting memories. Hitchin coming to pick you up.</p>

[ Ressler remembers Hitchin&#8217;s SUV pulling up, the window rolling down ]<br />
Hitchin: Agent Ressler.
</p></blockquote>
<p>Ressler: How do you know that?<br />

Hitchin: He&#8217;s the victim? I&#8217;m‚Äì<br />
Liz: Yes. And you&#8217;re a murderer. And one day, we&#8217;re gonna prove it.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />

Kate: Family feuds always do.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Werner&#8217;s dead.<br />
Kate: Oh, Raymond. You may have bitten the hand that feeds you this time, dearie. Every one of Werner&#8217;s allies will be out hunting to put you down. Are you going to cry havoc and let slip the dogs of war, Raymond?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Goodbye, Kate.<br />
[ Cellphone beeps ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Officer: Agent Ressler. Sorry, but I&#8217;m gonna need your sidearm.<br />
Ressler: Is that necessary?<br />
Officer: Yes, sir, it is.<br />
Liz: What are you doing?<br />
Officer: Will you just go ahead and turn around for me?<br />
Samar: Agent Ressler is the victim here. He was manipulated and drugged.<br />
Officer: I&#8217;m sure the investigation will bear that out. But in the meantime, he&#8217;s in our custody. Sir.[ The Officer leads Ressler away in handcuffs ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Hitchin: I really wanna thank you, Agent Keen. I genuinely believe he would&#8217;ve shot me if you hadn&#8217;t shown up.<br />
Liz: I didn&#8217;t do it for you. I did it for him.<br />
Hitchin: Fair enough, but you did it, and for that, I&#8217;m grateful.<br />
Liz: Donald Ressler represents what&#8217;s best about this country. He&#8217;s loyal and honest, and he believes that no one ‚Äì no one ‚Äì is above the law. And I believe that one day, you&#8217;ll be the one being dragged off in handcuffs. And he&#8217;ll be walking into his lake house to watch the sunset.<br />
Hitchin: [ Laughs ] Yeah. [ Clicks tongue ] Never gonna happen.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Liz: I want every detail ‚Äì what you did, how you did it, what memories you implanted in Agent Ressler&#8217;s consciousness, and what you took away. You&#8217;re going to give me everything we need to exonerate him.<br />
Dr Krilov: I could do that, I suppose, if properly motivated. You don&#8217;t remember me, do you?<br />
Liz: From 25 years ago? No. But then, you wouldn&#8217;t be very good at your job if I did.<br />
Dr Krilov: No. Not 25 years ago. Just two.<br />
Liz: What are you talking about?<br />
Dr Krilov: You were brought to me by a mutual acquaintance of ours who wanted me to take certain memories away from you.<br />
Liz: What memories?<br />
Dr Krilov: Let us say, you had uncovered certain truth about Raymond Reddington. And he couldn&#8217;t have that.<br />
Liz: You&#8217;re lying.<br />
Dr Krilov: No. I&#8217;m not lying. And I think you know that. So let&#8217;s make a deal. Full immunity, I walk, in exchange for the memories I took from you.<br />
Liz: That&#8217;s not gonna happen.<br />
Dr Krilov: [ Scoffs ] That is a shame for all of us. But more so for you, than me, I suspect. And for the  Agent Ressler, of course.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Liz on the phone with Red ] [ Liz is at home ]<br />
Liz: Two years ago? Two, not 25. Two.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Kaplan is using Krilov.<br />
Liz: What was the secret you needed Krilov to take away?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Nothing. She&#8217;s using him to pull at threads to continue to unravel my life. He sidelined Ressler. He&#8217;s trying to do the same to you.<br />
Liz: You did it once.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes. When you were a child, to protect you from the memory of killing your father. I hired Krilov once. Never again.<br />
Liz: [ Cellphone vibrates ] That&#8217;s Julian Gale. I&#8217;ve been avoiding his calls, and I&#8217;m beginning to think that was a mistake.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Bogdan Krilov and Julian Gale, directly or indirectly, they&#8217;re working for Kaplan against us.<br />
Liz: Against you.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;d think that would be a difficult distinction for you to make. Speak with him if you must. All I ask is that you don&#8217;t do it in anger. I wouldn&#8217;t want you to say anything either of us would regret.<br />
[ Bleating ] [ Red is with Dembe and others, including a boy about 8 years old, sitting on the floor of a truck transporting goats. The boy points towards Red&#8217;s hat. Red puts his hat on the boy&#8217;s head. The boy smiles. Red chuckles ] [ Bleating ]<br />
[ Aerosmith&#8217;s ‚ô™ &#8220;Dream On&#8221; plays ]<br />
&nbsp;<br />
[ Liz is at the ice rink morgue, looking around. Julian Gale comes up behind her ]<br />
Gale: Unfortunately, some of them were killed because they were trying to help us catch Reddington. I asked them to inform, I promised them protection, and, well, that failed. Here they are.<br />
Liz: You must be Agent Gale.<br />
Gale: Charmed, I&#8217;m sure. Speaking of charm, I hear Reddington can be very charming. What was it like going on the run with him? Did he charm you?<br />
Liz: I was a fugitive. It was awful.<br />
Gale: Hmm. September 23, 2013 ‚Äì Does that date ring a bell?<br />
Liz: Should it?<br />
Gale: It should for you. You see, that&#8217;s the day that you went from being a rookie profiler to a classified assignment. I always remember it. How &#8217;bout October 1, 2013? Nothin&#8217;? Really? [ Laughs ] See, that&#8217;s the date that the Reddington task force started to fall apart.<br />
Liz: I-I don&#8217;t know anything about that.<br />
Gale: No? How &#8217;bout SCI7? You ever hear of that?<br />
Liz: Never have.<br />
Gale: Well, apparently, it&#8217;s a designation that the Bureau reserves for certain high profile cases. It&#8217;s classified, so I can&#8217;t look at the files or interview the great American heroes of law enforcement that are doing such important work. However, I was able to pinpoint the first time that, uh, the designation was used. Do you care for another date? See, I love dates.<br />
Liz: Is there a question here?<br />
Gale: No, but-but there&#8217;s a pattern. See, there was a rash of major cases that were solved, hundreds of them. Started in the weeks after you were plucked from, uh, obscurity. Reddington&#8217;s been feeding the Bureau intel. Hmm? Big names. SCI7 big. Names that the Bureau never knew existed. He&#8217;s feeding them through you. And in exchange, you&#8217;re allowing him to stay one step ahead of the law, ain&#8217;t that right?<br />
Liz: Why did you wanna see me?<br />
Gale: I didn&#8217;t wanna see you. I wanted you to see that. [ Referring to the ice rink morgue and the  laid-out corpses ] See, I&#8217;ve already asked them for their forgiveness, for my part in their being‚Äì I wanted to give you a chance to do the same.</p>

<h3>‚≠ï Script 4:22 Mr Kaplan ‚Äì Conclusion (‚Ññ 4)</h3>
<blockquote><p>

<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Lou Reed&#8217;s ‚ô™ &#8220;Vicious&#8221; playing ]<br />
[ Red cuts up fake passports with his photo and other IDs into a metal wastebasket in a motel room ]<br />

<blockquote><p>

var WPGroHo = {"my_hash":""};
</script>
<script type='text/javascript' src='https://s0.wp.com/wp-content/mu-plugins/gravatar-hovercards/wpgroho.js?m=1380573781h'></script>

	<script>
		//initialize and attach hovercards to all gravatars
		jQuery( document ).ready( function( $ ) {

			if (typeof Gravatar === "undefined"){
				return;
			}

			if ( typeof Gravatar.init !== "function" ) {
				return;
			}			

			Gravatar.profile_cb = function( hash, id ) {
				WPGroHo.syncProfileData( hash, id );
			};
			Gravatar.my_hash = WPGroHo.my_hash;
			Gravatar.init( 'body', '#wp-admin-bar-my-account' );
		});
	</script>

		<div style="display:none">
	</div>
